he quality and accuracy of judgements persist.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 0.3pt; text-indent:-0.3pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">ATL </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">believes</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">profession-led local systems of accountability and improvement</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> would better serve young people’s education</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.3pt; text-indent:-0.3pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">This submission’s final section highlights </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">specific issues HMCI must address.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:15pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:15pt">Ofsted’s </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:15pt">annual report 2012-13</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 0.3pt; text-indent:-0.3pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">It is disappointing that despite the vast majority of schools being considered ‘outstanding’ or ‘good’ after Ofsted raised the bar in its inspection regime that the overwhelming </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">tone of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">mes</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">sages conveyed by the organisation’s launch of its annual report </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">is negative.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 0.3pt; text-indent:-0.3pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The patience afforded to academies </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">(paragraphs 48, 50) </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">does not appear to be matched by Ofsted with regards the non-acadamised maintained sector. The politicised </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">nature of the in</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">spectorate remains</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> inappropriate. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.3pt; text-indent:-0.3pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">In this annual report Ofsted repeats criticisms of teaching without acknowledging its own role in the proliferation of the characteristics listed (paragraph 37). This is symptomatic of constant moving of the goalposts and</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> exemplifies both the pressure and mistrust the teaching profession feels in relation to Ofsted.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:15pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:15pt">ATL’s evaluation of Ofsted 2012-13</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 0.3pt; text-indent:-0.3pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The main weakness of Ofsted is that it cannot guarantee the outcomes of its inspections process. Inconsistencies in the qua</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">lity and accura</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">cy of Ofsted judgements persist.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 0.3pt; text-indent:-0.3pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">ATL members have continued to report inconsistencies between inspectors, between inspections and between the experiences of different schools.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 0.3pt; text-indent:-0.3pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Our analysis of Ofsted’s subject surveys published in 2012 and 20</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">13 highlights further inconsistency, suggesting outcomes are unreliable, possibly pre-determined, and potentially politically driven. Despite this annual report stating that </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">almost eight </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">in ten</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> schools were found to be good or outstanding at their most rec</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">ent inspection, only one subject report, citizenship, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">in ten published, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">found a similar level of quality in schools.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 0.3pt; text-indent:-0.3pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">We are pleased Ofsted has required inspectors to have QTS but believe it continues to underestimate the challenge of maintaining an effecti</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">ve team of inspectors. The lack of quality control in the inspectorate is damaging not just to its own reputation but damaging to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">children’s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">’ education.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 0.3pt; text-indent:-0.3pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">ATL members find Ofsted’s public negativity towards teachers extremely demoralising. The flow of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">criticism raises stress rather than performance.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 0.3pt; text-indent:-0.3pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">A member from the primary sector</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> reports: “Previously graded consistently as </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">good</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">, we received </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">requires </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">improvement’</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">. We felt that some of the criticism was fair, but some unfair; however, we set to work </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">hard and improve … The process since Ofsted has been extremely negative.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">It seems to me that</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">a school with</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">some faults has now been completely destroyed as morale is very low; teachers continue to work extremely hard but feel</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">demoralised, depressed and exh</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">austed and support staff are also affected by the oppressive atmosphere in the school … This punitive regime has done nothing to improve the school.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 0.3pt; text-indent:-0.3pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">An ATL secondary school member</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">highlights the gap between effective accountability and the reality of Ofst</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">ed inspections: “It is 'all stick, and no carrot', but </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">it should </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">be about professional dialogue </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">and improving</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> the educational experience for </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">children.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:15pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:15pt">An Alternative </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 0.3pt; text-indent:-0.3pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">4.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Ofsted </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">can’t be relied upon for its judgments and can’t be counted on to play a role in</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> helping schools improve</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> because of its two major problems: inconsistency in quality and accuracy; and having next to no respect amongst the teaching profession.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 0.3pt; text-indent:-0.3pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">4.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">An</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> alternative</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> must address these issues and</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> ATL would like to see </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">profession-led local system</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">s of accountability and improvement.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 0.3pt; text-indent:-0.3pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">4.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">By being designed locally and with the involvement of current classroom teachers </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">judgments would be respected</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">unique </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">school circumstances better understood</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> and improvement plans would be relevant and effectively suppo</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">rted</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">. A national body such as Ofsted would have the role of overseeing the processes to quality assure them and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">provid</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">e confidence that </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">schools are</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> properly</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> accountable</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> in these new, local structures.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:15pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:15pt">Issues for the chief inspector to address</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 0.3pt; text-indent:-0.3pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">5.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Are </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">complaints and appeals against Ofsted inspection findings increasing?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 0.3pt; text-indent:-0.3pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">5.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Does Ofsted acknowledge it has a significant problem with its own quality control?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 0.3pt; text-indent:-0.3pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; fon